    discussions: [
      { item:"Westider Diner and Lounge Parklet Permit", body:"Owner Tyler Vote presented detailed mockups of a proposed parklet that would extend 4 feet into the street and 4 feet onto the sidewalk at 628 North Third Ave. He explained it would provide sunny seating for breakfast customers and would be lit with lighting for visibility. Alder Larson initially expressed reservations but changed position after seeing the layout. Watson moved to approve, Larson seconded, and the permit was approved unanimously for a summer 2026 trial with a November check-in planned." },
      { item:"Theodore Davis Bartender License Denial", body:"Davis appeared to address his denial recommendation, acknowledging his record and explaining he made a mistake 20 years ago as a minor that has followed him. His boyfriend Matthew Prieb also spoke in his support, describing Davis as a loving person who has not reoffended. The committee learned Davis had submitted evidence of rehabilitation to Chief Barnes but Deputy Chief Baiton was unfamiliar with the review results. The committee voted to hold the item until the next meeting to get Chief Barnes' updated recommendation." },
      { item:"Joanna Gregory Bartender License Denial", body:"Gregory did not appear at the meeting. Her denial was included in the batch motion for licenses as recommended by staff." },
      { item:"License Applications Batch Approval", body:"The committee approved summer events including Wings over Wausau, Concerts on the Square, Chalkfest, Memorial Day parade, Hope on the Block, and Jazz on the River. The liquor license review subcommittee recommended approval for Oasis Arcade, new ownership of Whiskey River Bar and Grill, and new owner for Hayawa. Motion by Larson, second by Watson, passed unanimously with Theodore Davis held for next meeting." },
      { item:"Solid Waste Disposal Ordinance Update", body:"Assistant City Attorney Vinnie Bonino presented the repealing and recreating of Chapter 6.44 to comply with state-level changes. Motion by Larson, second by Watson, approved unanimously with no discussion." },
      { item:"Handheld Mobile Phone Ban Repeal", body:"The committee repealed the local cell phone ban ordinance as state traffic laws have been amended to regulate cell phone usage, making the local ordinance redundant. Bonino explained the city already adopts the state traffic code. Motion by Watson, second by Larson, approved unanimously." },
      { item:"Midwest Renewable Energy Solar Partnership", body:"Carrie from the planning department reported the sustainability committee unanimously approved this item on March 5th. Alder Sarah Watson, who has solar on her house, praised the partnership with MREA for their expertise in helping navigate solar installation. Motion by Watson, second by Larson, approved unanimously." },
      { item:"Fire Department 2025 Annual Report", body:"Fire Chief reported the department set a new record with over 7,200 calls averaging 20 per day. He announced that as of Friday, the city regained ISO Class 2 status for the next four years. The committee discussed upcoming public information sessions on March 31st, April 1st at Station 2, and April 3rd at Station 1 related to the April 7th referendum. The report was placed on file." },
      { item:"Homeless Shelter Transition Update", body:"Tracy Durante reported 415 unduplicated guests served since opening and 740 volunteer hours in February. James Torensson, new Director of Homeless Services at Bridge Street Mission, explained the shelter transition is expected around late April, with WMC extending their contract through April 19th. Catholic Charities reported 99 unduplicated guests since November 1st. The committee expressed interest in touring the new facility at a ribbon cutting ceremony." },
    ],
    publicComment: "Carrie Mor Everest of 1025 Everest Boulevard spoke during late public comment about her concerns regarding treatment of unhoused individuals during 911 emergencies at the shelter. She stated she has volunteered at the shelter since it opened and witnessed multiple incidents where she felt people were not treated ethically or professionally. She expressed frustration that complaints she filed over 10 months have not been addressed and was directed to the Police and Fire Commission for formal complaints.",
